diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that often features symptoms including dry eyes and can contribute to systemic issues such as hypertension and blood pressure variability.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune inflammatory disorder that can cause chronic pain, including in the back, and systemic symptoms such as hypertension.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain, fatigue, and other symptoms including chronic back pain. Its relationship with blood pressure is more indirect, potentially affecting it through pain-related stress or sleep disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Hypertensive Heart Disease
diagnoses.description: Chronic high blood pressure (hypertension) can lead to heart disease. Symptoms may indirectly contribute to chronic pain through decreased circulation.

diagnoses.name: Osteoarthritis
diagnoses.description: A degenerative joint disease that can cause chronic back pain. While it does not directly cause dry eyes or hypertension, the stress from chronic pain and reduced mobility can indirectly affect blood pressure.

diagnoses.name: Ankylosing Spondylitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that can cause some of the vertebrae in your spine to fuse together, leading to chronic back pain. Systemic inflammation can potentially affect blood pressure.

diagnoses.name: Primary Hypertension
diagnoses.description: Also known as essential hypertension, is a condition where high blood pressure exists without a specific secondary cause. It can indirectly contribute to chronic pain via its effects on blood circulation.

diagnoses.name: Secondary Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A form of Sjögren's Syndrome that develops as a complication of another autoimmune disease. It shares many symptoms with primary Sjögren's Syndrome, including dry eyes and potential impacts on blood pressure.

diagnoses.name: Polymyalgia Rheumatica
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disorder causing muscle pain and stiffness, primarily in the shoulders. Symptoms like hypertension can occur, especially if giant cell arteritis is also present.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Sinusitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the sinuses that can lead to symptoms such as post-nasal drip. It doesn't directly cause hypertension or back pain, but the constant discomfort and poor sleep might increase blood pressure over time.

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses.comments: Iron deficiency anemia often presents with pallor and can cause general symptoms such as fatigue, which might indirectly affect libido. Though less common, some individuals might experience oral pain due to glossitis.

Rheumatoid arthritis is characterized by joint pain and can also cause systemic symptoms including fatigue and, in some cases, oral pain due to Sjögren's syndrome. The chronic nature of the disease could also impact libido indirectly.

Hypothyroidism can lead to symptoms such as fatigue, joint pain, and pallor. Decreased libido is a common complaint. Though oral pain is not a typical symptom, hypothyroidism can lead to a slowed metabolism and associated symptoms.

Vitamin B12 deficiency can lead to pallor due to anemia and might cause oral pain due to glossitis. Joint pain and a decrease in libido can also be associated symptoms due to overall weakness and neuropathy.

Fibromyalgia is often associated with diffuse joint and muscle pain. Patients might report decreased libido due to chronic pain and fatigue. Oral pain is less commonly directly related but could be due to associated conditions like TMJ disorders.

Chronic kidney disease can cause pallor due to anemia and joint pain due to calcium-phosphorus imbalance. Decreased libido is often reported. Oral pain could come from associated secondary hyperparathyroidism or xerostomia.

Depression can manifest physically, leading to chronic pain including joint pain. Decreased libido is a common symptom of depression. Oral pain might not be directly caused by depression but could be related to associated behaviors or conditions.
Sjögren's syndrome directly causes oral pain due to dry mouth and can contribute to joint pain. The chronic nature and the discomfort from dryness can indirectly affect libido.
SLE can cause joint pain and pallor due to anemia. Chronic systemic symptoms may contribute to decreased libido. Oral pain can occur due to ulcerations.

Certain STIs can indirectly cause joint pain and oral pain (e.g., syphilis can cause oral lesions). Pallor could result from anemia associated with chronic infection. Decreased libido can be a direct symptom or result from psychological factors related to the STI.

diagnoses.name: Connective Tissue Disorder
diagnoses.description: Disorders that affect the proteins that play a role in the support and structure of organs and tissues in the body. Symptoms can include aneurysms, poor healing, and various respiratory issues.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD)
diagnoses.description: A group of lung diseases that block airflow and make it difficult to breathe. Chronic bronchitis is a primary component, and systemic issues can lead to symptoms like poor healing.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the blood vessels that can cause aneurysms or rupture of blood vessels, leading to organ damage and a variety of symptoms including bronchitis and irritability.

diagnoses.name: Neurofibromatosis
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that causes tumors to form on nerve tissue. These tumors can develop anywhere in your nervous system, including the brain, spinal cord, and nerves. The condition can lead to a variety of neurological symptoms, including difficulties with cognitive functions such as word-finding.

diagnoses.name: Fibromuscular Dysplasia
diagnoses.description: A condition that causes abnormal growth or development of cells in the walls of blood vessels that can lead to aneurysms, high blood pressure, and a range of other symptoms depending on the affected arteries.

diagnoses.name: Marfan Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An inherited disorder that affects connective tissue — the fibers that support and anchor your organs and other structures in your body. Marfan syndrome can lead to aneurysms, particularly in the aorta, and may also impact healing.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders that affect connective tissues supporting the skin, bones, blood vessels, and many other organs and tissues. This can lead to poor healing, aneurysms, and possibly respiratory issues.

diagnoses.name: Lupus
diagnoses.description: A systemic autoimmune disease that occurs when your body's immune system attacks your own tissues and organs. Symptoms vary but can include poor healing, irritability, and lung issues such as bronchitis.

diagnoses.name: Bacterial Endocarditis
diagnoses.description: An infection of the inner lining of your heart chambers and heart valves. It can cause fever, poor healing, and a variety of symptoms depending on which parts of the body are affected.

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.description: A type of blood cancer that causes the bone marrow to make too many red blood cells. These excess cells thicken your blood, slowing its flow, which can lead to complications including difficulty breathing and healing.

diagnoses: Inflammatory Bowel Disease (Crohn's disease and Ulcerative Colitis)
Inflammatory bowel disease (Crohn's disease or ulcerative colitis)

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic, typically progressive disease involving damage to the sheaths of nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord, symptoms may include numbness, impairment of speech and of muscular coordination, blurred vision and severe fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of migraine that involves neurological phenomena (aura) like visual disturbances and other sensory disturbances that precede the headache phase of the migraines.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: Occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Symptoms depend on the size, location, and rate of growth of the tumor.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular Neuritis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the vestibular nerve, a nerve in the ear that helps control balance. This condition causes vertigo.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a TIA is a brief, temporary disruption of blood supply to part of the brain, spinal cord, or retina, which may cause symptoms similar to those of a stroke.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barré Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare neurological disorder in which the body's immune system mistakenly attacks part of its peripheral nervous system—the network of nerves located outside of the brain and spinal cord.

diagnoses.name: Ménière's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear that can lead to dizzy spells (vertigo) and hearing loss. In most cases, Ménière's disease affects only one ear.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.description: A noncancerous and usually slow-growing tumor that develops on the main nerve leading from your inner ear to your brain. As the neuroma grows, it presses against the hearing and balance nerves.

diagnoses.name: Metabolic Encephalopathy
diagnoses.description: A term used to describe a variety of brain disorders resulting from alterations in the brain's chemistry due to liver disease, kidney disease, severe infections, or failure of another organ system.
